# Memory and ownership

See the ownership table in [docs/architecture.md](docs/architecture.md). Every allocation has one owner and one dispose path.

## Lifecycle pairs

| Allocate / init | Free / shutdown |
|-----------------|-----------------|
| `csvi_viewer_create` | `csvi_viewer_destroy` |
| `csv_reader_read_file` | `csv_contents_dispose` |
| `matrix_config_initialize` | `matrix_config_dispose` |
| `commands_init` | `commands_shutdown` |
| `matrix_presentation_init` | `matrix_presentation_exit` / `matrix_presentation_shutdown` |

New resources must follow the same pattern: `*_create`/`*_init` paired with `*_destroy`/`*_dispose`/`*_shutdown`.

## Rules

- Every `malloc`/`calloc` has a matching `free` on **all** paths (including early returns).
- Library code under `src/lib/` never calls `exit()` — return error codes or NULL.
- I/O failures: return NULL and fill `errbuf`, or return an `int` that `main` maps to `CSVI_EXIT_*`.
- Prefer opaque types for public state (`typedef struct csvi_viewer_t csvi_viewer_t` in header; definition in `.c`).

```c
// BAD — caller cannot free or handle error
csv_contents *load(const char *path) {
    if (!fp) exit(1);
}

// GOOD — caller owns result and gets a message
csv_contents *csv_reader_read_file(const char *path, char *errbuf, size_t errbuf_len);
```
